    "cpap-body-1": {
      "type": "rich-text",
      "blocks": {
        "cpap-text-1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>If you're one of the 22 million Americans who've been prescribed a CPAP machine, you know the drill.</strong> The hissing mask. The tangled hose. The red marks on your face every morning. The constant fight with your partner over the Darth Vader noise. And the guilt — that sinking feeling every time you \"forget\" to put it on, knowing you're risking your health but just... can't... do it anymore.</p><p>You're not alone. Studies show that <strong>nearly 50% of CPAP users abandon their therapy within the first year.</strong> Not because it doesn't work — but because it's unbearable.</p><p>For years, the medical establishment had one answer: \"Try harder. Try a different mask. Try a chin strap. Try sleeping sitting up.\"</p><p><strong>But one man refused to accept that answer.</strong></p>",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "text_size": 16,
            "margin_top": 12,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "cpap-text-1"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "display_id": false,
        "visibility": "always-display",
        "full_width": false,
        "mobile_narrow_width": false,
        "color_scheme": "background-1",
        "padding_top": 12,
        "padding_bottom": 12
      }
    },
    "cpap-body-2": {
      "type": "rich-text",
      "blocks": {
        "cpap-heading-2": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Meet Dr. Alan Crawford — The Pacemaker Engineer Who Couldn't Sleep",
            "title_highlight_1": "none",
            "title_highlight_2": "none",
            "heading_size": "h2",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "margin_top": 21,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        },
        "cpap-text-2": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Dr. Alan Crawford spent 15 years at a leading medical device company designing pacemakers — the kind that go <em>inside</em> your body, save your life, and you forget they're even there.</p><p>Then, at age 52, he was diagnosed with severe obstructive sleep apnea. His AHI was 41 — meaning his breathing stopped 41 times per hour. Every. Single. Night.</p><p>His doctor handed him a CPAP machine. And for the first time in his career, Alan experienced what it felt like to be on the patient side of a poorly designed medical device.</p><p>\"I spent 15 years designing devices that patients never see or feel,\" Crawford recalls. \"And here I was, strapping a vacuum cleaner to my face every night. I thought — there has to be a better way. This is 2026. We have self-driving cars. We have AI that can detect cancer. And we're still putting masks and hoses on people's faces?\"</p><p>He started digging into the research. And what he found shocked him.</p>",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "text_size": 16,
            "margin_top": 9,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "cpap-heading-2",
        "cpap-text-2"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "display_id": false,
        "visibility": "always-display",
        "full_width": false,
        "mobile_narrow_width": false,
        "color_scheme": "background-1",
        "padding_top": 12,
        "padding_bottom": 12
      }
    },
    "cpap-body-3": {
      "type": "rich-text",
      "blocks": {
        "cpap-heading-3": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What the CPAP Industry Doesn't Want You to Know",
            "title_highlight_1": "none",
            "title_highlight_2": "none",
            "heading_size": "h2",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "margin_top": 21,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        },
        "cpap-text-3": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Here's the truth the $6.2 billion CPAP industry would rather keep quiet:</p><p><strong>CPAP doesn't cure sleep apnea. It manages it — badly.</strong> The mask doesn't fix the root cause of your airway collapsing. It just forces air through it. Stop using it for one night, and you're right back where you started.</p><p>And the real scandal? <strong>Your jaw position is the key — and CPAP does nothing about it.</strong></p><p>When you sleep, your lower jaw relaxes and falls backward, dragging your tongue with it. That's what blocks your airway. It's simple physics. CPAP fights this with brute force — pressurized air. But what if you could prevent the jaw from falling back in the first place?</p><p>That's exactly what Dr. Crawford set out to do.</p>",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "text_size": 16,
            "margin_top": 9,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "cpap-heading-3",
        "cpap-text-3"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "display_id": false,
        "visibility": "always-display",
        "full_width": false,
        "mobile_narrow_width": false,
        "color_scheme": "background-1",
        "padding_top": 12,
        "padding_bottom": 12
      }
    },
    "cpap-body-4": {
      "type": "rich-text",
      "blocks": {
        "cpap-heading-4": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Introducing AirwayPro™ — The No-Mask, No-Hose, No-Mouthpiece Solution",
            "title_highlight_1": "none",
            "title_highlight_2": "none",
            "heading_size": "h2",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "margin_top": 21,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        },
        "cpap-text-4": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>After three years of prototyping, testing, and refinement, Dr. Crawford unveiled <strong>AirwayPro™</strong> — a revolutionary device that addresses sleep apnea at its anatomical source.</p><p>AirwayPro™ is a small, comfortable device worn <strong>externally under the chin</strong> during sleep. Using a patented <strong>gentle support technology</strong>, it prevents your lower jaw from collapsing backward — keeping your airway naturally open all night long.</p><p><strong>No mask on your face. No hose snaking across your bed. No mouthpiece crammed between your teeth. No electricity. No noise.</strong></p><p>Just natural, unobstructed breathing — the way your body was designed to sleep.</p><p>\"It's almost embarrassingly simple,\" Crawford says. \"The jaw falls back → airway closes → you stop breathing. So... stop the jaw from falling back. We don't need a pressurized air system for that. We just need a gentle, comfortable support.\"</p>",
            "alignment": "left",
            "mobile_alignment": "mobile-left",
            "text_size": 16,
            "margin_top": 9,
            "margin_bottom": 12
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "cpap-heading-4",
        "cpap-text-4"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "display_id": false,
        "visibility": "always-display",
        "full_width": false,
        "mobile_narrow_width": false,
        "color_scheme": "background-1",
